column1: cause of death (extensive list of 'three digit codes')
This table contains the number of deaths in the population of the Netherlands by underlying cause of death. The causes of death are shown according to the extensive list of 'three digit codes'

Since 2013 Statistics Netherlands is using Iris software for automatic coding for cause of death. This improved the international comparison of the data. The change in coding did cause a considerable shift in the statistic. Since 2013 the (yearly) ICD-10 updates are applied.
Figures up until and including 2020 are final. Figures of 2021 are provisional
The provisional figures for 2021 have been added.
In the figures of 2020 in some age groups with 'I00-I99 Diseases of the circulatory system' as cause of death
column2: the numbers were invisible. That has now been restored.

column1: As of 2020 'COVID-19' has been added to the causes of death.
When will new figures be published?
The aim is to publish final figures for 2021 in the fourth quarter of 2022.

column1: As of 2020 'COVID-19' has been added to the causes of death.
When will new figures be published?
The aim is to publish final figures for 2021 in the fourth quarter of 2022.
Underlying (formerly called: primary) cause of death
The causes of death used in this table are the 'three digit codes' according to the International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health (ICD10
column2: 10th revision) of the World Health Organization.

column1: WHO defines an underlying cause of death as: (a) the disease or disorder that initiates the causal chain of diseases or disorders leading directly to death (natural death); (b) the circumstances of the accident or violence causing the injury that initiated the causal chain of morbid events leading directly to death (non-natural death).
In order to properly map the mortality due to COVID-19 for statistical purposes
column2: death due to COVID-19 is defined as death due to a clinically compatible disease
column3: in case of confirmed or suspected/probable COVID-19
column4: unless there is a clear other cause of death that can not be related to COVID-19 (e.g. injury or accident). There can not be a period of full recovery from COVID-19 between illness and death.

column1: Classification and coding of COVID-19 for de Mortality statistics according to the WHO guidelines:

column2: virus identified COVID-19 NOS - confirmed diagnosis of COVID-19 - when COVID-19 has been confirmed by laboratory testing and clinical signs or symptoms.
suspected or probable COVID-19 - clinical or epidemiological diagnosis (suspected or probable) of COVID-19 but laboratory testing is inconclusive or not available.

column1: The figures refer to the deaths of the Dutch resident population
column2: i.e. persons included in municipal population registers (in the Netherlands: the Key Register of Persons (BRP)).
